<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="149" pageId="19" pageNumber="148" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="148">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="149" pageId="19" pageNumber="148">
Head slightly small (Figure 22); [8 supralabials, second in contact with prefrontal, third and fourth or third, fourth and fifth touch eye (
<bibRefCitation pageId="19" pageNumber="148">Gasperetti 1988</bibRefCitation>
)] (Figure 21); body elongate but not markedly slender anteriorly (Figure 22); [290-404 ventrals (
<bibRefCitation author="Volsoe, H" editor="Jessen, K" journalOrPublisher="Copenhagen" pageId="30" pageNumber="159" pagination="9 - 45" title="The sea snakes of the Iranian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman, with a summary of the biology of the sea snakes." volumeTitle="Danish Scientific Investigations in Iran" year="1939">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Volsøe">Volsoe</normalizedToken>
1939
</bibRefCitation>
)], slightly distinguishable from adjacent scales (Figure 4d); body 
<pageBreakToken pageId="20" pageNumber="149" start="start">scales</pageBreakToken>
in thickest part of body more or less quadrangular or hexagonal in shape and juxtaposed; [29-31 scale rows on neck, 41-46 on body (
<bibRefCitation author="Volsoe, H" editor="Jessen, K" journalOrPublisher="Copenhagen" pageId="30" pageNumber="159" pagination="9 - 45" title="The sea snakes of the Iranian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman, with a summary of the biology of the sea snakes." volumeTitle="Danish Scientific Investigations in Iran" year="1939">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Volsøe">Volsoe</normalizedToken>
1939
</bibRefCitation>
)].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="20" pageNumber="149" type="coloration">
<paragraph pageId="20" pageNumber="149">Coloration.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="20" pageNumber="149">
Body olive-whitish, dirty white, darker dorsally and paler ventrally; [41-55 (
<bibRefCitation author="Volsoe, H" editor="Jessen, K" journalOrPublisher="Copenhagen" pageId="30" pageNumber="159" pagination="9 - 45" title="The sea snakes of the Iranian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman, with a summary of the biology of the sea snakes." volumeTitle="Danish Scientific Investigations in Iran" year="1939">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Volsøe">Volsoe</normalizedToken>
1939
</bibRefCitation>
)] black rings broader dorsally, or broader bands tapering to points on the sides, on the body and tail (Figure 22a); head black in juveniles, usually 
<pageBreakToken pageId="21" pageNumber="150" start="start">with</pageBreakToken>
a yellow horseshoe-shaped mark above; adults with head sometimes of same color as body without the horseshoe-shaped mark.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
